      Robinhood retail
   =20
 =20
The basic way an initial public offering works is:=09A company hires banks =
to market its stock to big institutional investors and build a book of dema=
nd from those investors.=09After reviewing the order book, the company and =
the banks price and allocate the stock one evening, selling it to those ins=
titutional investors at the market-clearing price that they=E2=80=99re will=
ing to pay.=09The next day, the stock opens for trading on the stock exchan=
ge, and ordinary retail investors get to buy it. They don=E2=80=99t care wh=
at price they pay. So=C2=A0some of the institutional investors who bought t=
he stock=C2=A0in Step 2 flip it to retail investors on Robinhood for a quic=
k profit.=C2=A0In Step 2, the company and the banks try to allocate the sto=
ck mostly to long-term shareholders who do not intend to flip it, which mea=
ns that there will not be all that much supply in Step 3. And because=C2=A0=
the retail investors couldn=E2=80=99t buy it at the IPO price in Step 2, th=
ey have to buy it at the public price in Step 3, which means that there wil=
l automatically be demand. Maybe not if it=E2=80=99s a boring company, but =
if it=E2=80=99s some sexy consumer-facing tech company then a lot of retail=
 investors will want to buy it in Step 3 and will push up the price, so the=
re will be a nice =E2=80=9CIPO pop=E2=80=9D: If you buy at the IPO price, y=
ou can sell at a much higher price the next day.Everyone knows this, though=
, so this is only the very first level of the analysis. If everyone in Step=
 2 thinks =E2=80=9Cthis is a big sexy consumer tech company so I will overp=
ay for it and then flip it to retail tomorrow,=E2=80=9D then there will be =
a lot of supply in Step 3 (everyone who bought in the IPO is flipping) and =
not much demand (no professional value investor wants to add to its positio=
n in the public market, and even retail thinks the price is too rich), so t=
he stock will actually fall. Most IPOs have a nice pop, but some of the big=
gest and sexiest consumer-facing tech IPOs (Facebook Inc.,  Uber Technologi=
es Inc.) fell in early trading because, roughly speaking, they were too ove=
r-hyped.Similarly. If you look at the three steps I laid out above, you mig=
ht say, well, if the retail investors are willing to pay more than the inst=
itutional investors, and IPOs=C2=A0usually pop, why should the institutiona=
l investors get to profit from that? Why shouldn=E2=80=99t the company sell=
 some stock to retail investors in Step 2? This reduces the number of share=
s it needs to sell to institutions, which allows it to drive a harder barga=
in with them and get a higher market-clearing price, meaning more money for=
 the company and a smaller IPO pop. (Assuming, as everyone does, that the r=
etail investors are not price-sensitive and will just buy at whatever price=
 the institutions pay.) And in fact  I have argued that this is a good inst=
inct to have and that Robinhood Markets Inc., the leading brokerage for pri=
ce-insensitive retail investors, should encourage companies to do that.=C2=
=A0But this again is all first-order stuff and you have to think about how =
it will be received. If you are selling fewer shares to institutions, then =
in theory you might be able to get a higher price.[1] But if the reason tha=
t you are selling fewer shares to institutions is that you are selling a bu=
nch of shares to retail to=C2=A0anticipate and lessen=C2=A0the IPO pop, the=
n the institutions will demand a lower price. =E2=80=9CI would pay $50 per =
share if I knew a bunch of retail investors will be waiting to buy from me =
at $60 the next day, but if you=E2=80=99re selling stock to any retail inve=
stors who want it then that goes away and I=E2=80=99ll only pay $45.=E2=80=
=9D It is not really clear which effect dominates.I guess we=E2=80=99ll fin=
d out tomorrow?=C2=A0Robinhood is  pricing its own IPO tonight:The company =
behind the trading app that starred in this year=E2=80=99s meme stock run-u=
p is carving out an unusually large role for those very same novice investo=
rs. On Thursday, when its shares are expected to begin trading after they p=
rice late Wednesday, the wisdom of that strategy will be put to the test.Th=
e interests of bankers, founders and employees may not always align, but th=
ey all typically cross their fingers for a company=E2=80=99s stock price to=
 =E2=80=9Cpop=E2=80=9D much higher once it begins trading after an initial =
public offering. That boost is important because it tends to indicate stron=
g demand among individual investors who couldn=E2=80=99t get their hands on=
 shares before they hit the exchange.That=E2=80=99s not the case for Robinh=
ood, which has said it will reserve up to 35% of shares for its app users a=
t the pre-trading range of $38 to $42 apiece. Chief Executive Officer Vlad =
Tenev said in a live-streamed roadshow on Saturday that it will likely be o=
ne of the largest such allocations to retail investors ever.While that deci=
sion fits with Robinhood=E2=80=99s self-described mission of =E2=80=9Cdemoc=
ratizing finance,=E2=80=9D it also sets the company up for a make-or-break =
moment when its shares begin trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market under the s=
ymbol HOOD.It=E2=80=99s like any exclusive club: The reason that people wan=
t to be able to buy stocks at the IPO price is because a lot of people can=
=E2=80=99t; if you let everyone do it, it stops being cool. If retail inves=
tors mostly can't buy a stock at the IPO price, they=E2=80=99ll be lining u=
p to buy it the next day, and if you were special and got to buy at the IPO=
 price then you can make a quick profit. If everyone buys at the IPO price =
then there'll be no one waiting to buy it the next day, and everyone who bo=
ught it to make a quick profit will be selling it at a loss.Or they won=E2=
=80=99t, of course, because they have diamond hands and like the stock. I h=
ave no idea how any of this will go, and I doubt anyone else does either. P=
eople are certainly nervous though:The decision by retail brokerage app Rob=
inhood to reserve an unusually large stake in its initial public offering t=
his week for its own customers has money managers girding for a volatile tr=
ading debut. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CEverybody expects more volatility in the tra=
ding, that=E2=80=99s it,=E2=80=9D said one equities trader at a large New Y=
ork asset manager. =E2=80=9CThe more stock in retail hands, the more volati=
le it is.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Is that right? I feel like the real meme-stock vola=
tility is when retail investors=C2=A0decide=C2=A0to get into a stock that t=
hey=C2=A0aren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0in, when it migrates from institutional hands =
to retail hands. Like what happened to GameStop Corp. in January, or what o=
ften happens to IPO stocks on their first day of trading. Robinhood is goin=
g to=C2=A0have=C2=A0a lot of retail investors, not because it is allocating=
 a lot of stock to them in the IPO but because it is Robinhood and its cust=
omers are going to buy it one way or another. Allocating a lot of stock to =
them in the IPO just makes that transition smoother.=C2=A0I wrote recently:=
If you allocate shares to the Robinhood traders to begin with =E2=80=94 in =
the IPO, at a price set mainly by the institutional investors who care abou=
t valuation =E2=80=94=C2=A0then there will be less of a retail rush to buy =
stock the next day, and the stock will trade at closer to its IPO price.I s=
hould emphasize that this is not investment advice and I am probably wrong?=
 Like, one, I=E2=80=99m wrong about every prediction I make, and, two, in t=
his case there keep being articles quoting professionals saying =E2=80=9Cth=
is is going to be a wild one=E2=80=9D and you should probably believe them =
instead of me.=C2=A0I am just laying out my thinking here so we can underst=
and how I=E2=80=99ll be wrong.
