adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Robinhood retail</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic way <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24580483.273146/aHR0cHM6Ly9hMTZ6LmNvbS8yMD=
IwLzA4LzI4L2luLWRlZmVuc2Utb2YtdGhlLWlwby8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb3e7a1a9=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">an initi=
al public offering works</a> is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; =
padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A=
 company hires banks to market its stock to big institutional investors and=
 build a book of demand from those investors.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">After reviewing the order book, the company and the banks price=
 and allocate the stock one evening, selling it to those institutional inve=
stors at the market-clearing price that they=E2=80=99re willing to pay.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The next day, the stock opens for tra=
ding on the stock exchange, and ordinary retail investors get to buy it. Th=
ey don=E2=80=99t care what price they pay. So=C2=A0some of the institutiona=
l investors who bought the stock=C2=A0in Step 2 flip it to retail investors=
 on Robinhood for a quick profit.=C2=A0</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">In Step 2, the company and the banks try to allocate the stock mostly to=
 long-term shareholders who do not intend to flip it, which means that ther=
e will not be all that much supply in Step 3. And because=C2=A0the retail i=
nvestors couldn=E2=80=99t buy it at the IPO price in Step 2, they have to b=
uy it at the public price in Step 3, which means that there will automatica=
lly be demand. Maybe not if it=E2=80=99s a boring company, but if it=E2=80=
=99s some sexy consumer-facing tech company then a lot of retail investors =
will want to buy it in Step 3 and will push up the price, so there will be =
a nice =E2=80=9CIPO pop=E2=80=9D: If you buy at the IPO price, you can sell=
 at a much higher price the next day.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every=
one knows this, though, so this is only the very first level of the analysi=
s. If everyone in Step 2 thinks =E2=80=9Cthis is a big sexy consumer tech c=
ompany so I will overpay for it and then flip it to retail tomorrow,=E2=80=
=9D then there will be a lot of supply in Step 3 (everyone who bought in th=
e IPO is flipping) and not much demand (no professional value investor want=
s to add to its position in the public market, and even retail thinks the p=
rice is too rich), so the stock will actually fall. Most IPOs have a nice p=
op, but some of the biggest and sexiest consumer-facing tech IPOs (<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24580483.273146/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAxMi8wNS8yMS9mYWNlYm9vay1zaGFyZXMtZmFsbC1iZWxvdy1pcG8t=
b2ZmZXJpbmctcHJpY2UuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5e821f85" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Facebook Inc.</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24580483.273146/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDUtMTQvdGhlcmUtd=
2FzLW5vLXdheS10by13aW4td2l0aC10aGUtdWJlci1pcG8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe53=
98e16" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Ub=
er Technologies Inc.</a>) fell in early trading because, roughly speaking, =
they were too over-hyped.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly. If you=
 look at the three steps I laid out above, you might say, well, if the reta=
il investors are willing to pay more than the institutional investors, and =
IPOs=C2=A0usually pop, why should the institutional investors get to profit=
 from that? Why shouldn=E2=80=99t the company sell some stock to retail inv=
estors in Step 2? This reduces the number of shares it needs to sell to ins=
titutions, which allows it to drive a harder bargain with them and get a hi=
gher market-clearing price, meaning more money for the company and a smalle=
r IPO pop. (Assuming, as everyone does, that the retail investors are not p=
rice-sensitive and will just buy at whatever price the institutions pay.) A=
nd in fact <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2458048=
3.273146/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMD=
UtMjQvbWVycmlsbC1seW5jaC1wdXRzLWRvd24tdGhlLXBob25l/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B5c1e2bb0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> I have argued</a> that this is a good instinct to have and that Robinhood=
 Markets Inc., the leading brokerage for price-insensitive retail investors=
, should encourage companies to do that.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">But this again is all first-order stuff and you have to think about how=
 it will be received. If you are selling fewer shares to institutions, then=
 in theory you might be able to get a higher price.[1] But if the reason th=
at you are selling fewer shares to institutions is that you are selling a b=
unch of shares to retail to=C2=A0anticipate and lessen=C2=A0the IPO pop, th=
en the institutions will demand a lower price. =E2=80=9CI would pay $50 per=
 share if I knew a bunch of retail investors will be waiting to buy from me=
 at $60 the next day, but if you=E2=80=99re selling stock to any retail inv=
estors who want it then that goes away and I=E2=80=99ll only pay $45.=E2=80=
=9D It is not really clear which effect dominates.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">I guess we=E2=80=99ll find out tomorrow?=C2=A0Robinhood is <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24580483.273146/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjgvcm9iaW5ob29kLWJh=
bmtzLW9uLWl0cy10cmFkZXJzLWFsbGVnaWFuY2UtaW4taXBvLWxpa2Utbm8tb3RoZXI/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB9b7b1b01" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> pricing its own IPO tonight</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company behind the trading app that starred in thi=
s year=E2=80=99s meme stock run-up is carving out an unusually large role f=
or those very same novice investors. On Thursday, when its shares are expec=
ted to begin trading after they price late Wednesday, the wisdom of that st=
rategy will be put to the test.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The interes=
ts of bankers, founders and employees may not always align, but they all ty=
pically cross their fingers for a company=E2=80=99s stock price to =E2=80=
=9Cpop=E2=80=9D much higher once it begins trading after an initial public =
offering. That boost is important because it tends to indicate strong deman=
d among individual investors who couldn=E2=80=99t get their hands on shares=
 before they hit the exchange.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=
=99s not the case for Robinhood, which has said it will reserve up to 35% o=
f shares for its app users at the pre-trading range of $38 to $42 apiece. C=
hief Executive Officer Vlad Tenev said in a live-streamed roadshow on Satur=
day that it will likely be one of the largest such allocations to retail in=
vestors ever.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While that decision fits with=
 Robinhood=E2=80=99s self-described mission of =E2=80=9Cdemocratizing finan=
ce,=E2=80=9D it also sets the company up for a make-or-break moment when it=
s shares begin trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market under the symbol HOOD.</p=
></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s like any exclusive =
club: The reason that people want to be able to buy stocks at the IPO price=
 is because a lot of people can=E2=80=99t; if you let everyone do it, it st=
ops being cool. If retail investors mostly can't buy a stock at the IPO pri=
ce, they=E2=80=99ll be lining up to buy it the next day, and if you were sp=
ecial and got to buy at the IPO price then you can make a quick profit. If =
everyone buys at the IPO price then there'll be no one waiting to buy it th=
e next day, and everyone who bought it to make a quick profit will be selli=
ng it at a loss.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or they won=E2=80=99t, of =
course, because they have diamond hands and like the stock. I have no idea =
how any of this will go, and I doubt anyone else does either. People are <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24580483.273146/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZWU3NTVjMDItZGQwOS00MDQxLThiMTQtZWZhZDMwYTY=
2MmE2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB53ba8342" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">certainly nervous though</a>:</p><blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The decision by retail brokerage app Robinh=
ood to reserve an unusually large stake in its initial public offering this=
 week for its own customers has money managers girding for a volatile tradi=
ng debut. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CEverybody expe=
cts more volatility in the trading, that=E2=80=99s it,=E2=80=9D said one eq=
uities trader at a large New York asset manager. =E2=80=9CThe more stock in=
 retail hands, the more volatile it is.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is that right? I feel like the real meme-stock vol=
atility is when retail investors=C2=A0<em>decide=C2=A0</em>to get into a st=
ock that they=C2=A0<em>aren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>in, when it migrates from i=
nstitutional hands to retail hands. Like what happened to GameStop Corp. in=
 January, or what often happens to IPO stocks on their first day of trading=
. Robinhood is going to=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>a lot of retail investors, =
not because it is allocating a lot of stock to them in the IPO but because =
it is Robinhood and its customers are going to buy it one way or another. A=
llocating a lot of stock to them in the IPO just makes that transition <em>=
smoother</em>.=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/24580483.273146/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjEtMDctMDIvcm9iaW5ob29kLWlwby1maWxpbmctaXMtYS1sZXNzb24taW4tbWVtZS1maW5h=
bmNl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf6d334d1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">I wrote recently</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you allocate shares to the Robinhood traders to beg=
in with =E2=80=94 in the IPO, at a price set mainly by the institutional in=
vestors who care about valuation =E2=80=94=C2=A0then there will be less of =
a retail rush to buy stock the next day, and the stock will trade at closer=
 to its IPO price.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I should em=
phasize that this is not investment advice and I am probably wrong? Like, o=
ne, I=E2=80=99m wrong about every prediction I make, and, two, in this case=
 there keep being articles quoting professionals saying =E2=80=9Cthis is go=
ing to be a wild one=E2=80=9D and you should probably believe them instead =
of me.=C2=A0I am just laying out my thinking here so we can understand how =
I=E2=80=99ll be wrong.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"=
0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Assorted small Robinhood scandals</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><span>Here=E2=80=99s an update in Robi=
nhood Markets Inc.=E2=80=99s </span><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/24580483.273146/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZ=
Gdhci9kYXRhLzE3ODM4NzkvMDAwMTYyODI4MDIxMDE0NDg4L3JvYmluaG9vZHMtMWEyLmh0bQ/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBce813d4b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">latest revised prospectus</a><span> for its initial=
 public offering:</span></p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Beginn=
ing on January 28, 2021, due to increased deposit requirements imposed on [=
Robinhood]=C2=A0by the NSCC in response to unprecedented market volatility,=
 particularly in certain securities, [Robinhood] temporarily restricted or =
limited its customers=E2=80=99 purchase of certain securities, including Ga=
meStop Corp. and AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc., on our platform (the =E2=
=80=9CEarly 2021 Trading Restrictions=E2=80=9D). =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">We have also received inquiries from the SEC=E2=80=99s Divi=
sion of Examinations and FINRA related to employee trading in certain secur=
ities that were subject to the Early 2021 Trading Restrictions, including G=
ameStop Corp. and AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc., during the week of Janu=
ary 25, 2021. These matters include inquiries related to whether any employ=
ee trading in these securities may have occurred in advance of the public a=
nnouncement of the Early 2021 Trading Restrictions on January 28, 2021.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously it is=C2=A0<em>p=
ossible=C2=A0</em>that some Robinhood employee bought GameStop stock, learn=
ed that Robinhood was about to restrict trading in GameStop, and dumped all=
 of her GameStop shares moments before the restrictions kicked in in order =
to avoid losing money. And that would be bad and would get her in trouble w=
ith the Securities and Exchange Commission and the Financial Industry Regul=
atory Authority. It seems like a weirdly blatant thing to do, and I wouldn=
=E2=80=99t expect an employee of a regulated broker-dealer to do it, but, u=
h, Robinhood sometimes <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/24580483.273146/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbG=
VzLzIwMTgtMTItMTcvcm9iaW5ob29kLWNoZWNraW5nLW1vdmVkLWZhc3QtYW5kLWJyb2tl/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB059771ff" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> does things that I wouldn=E2=80=99t expect</a>, from =
a regulatory perspective.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the othe=
r hand if you were a Robinhood employee who was <em>totally innocently=C2=
=A0</em>trading meme stocks during the week of Jan. 25, you might well have=
=C2=A0<em>totally innocently=C2=A0</em>sold your GameStop on Jan. 27. Perha=
ps you bought the stock on Monday, Jan.=C2=A025, when it was a meme that ev=
eryone was talking about; it closed at $76.79 that day. By Wednesday, Jan. =
27, it closed at $347.51. You might have decided to sell because you were u=
p like 350%? Like, good trade, well done, take some profits. And then the n=
ext day your employer announces that it has restricted trading in GameStop =
and, on the one hand, phew, you got out just in time, but on the other hand=
, oops, you=E2=80=99re gonna get calls from the SEC and Finra.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose one question here is: Is it <em>good</em>, i=
f a lot of employees of a big retail brokerage are day-trading meme stocks =
in their personal accounts? On the one hand, it creates obvious risks of co=
nflict of interest and trading on inside information, as is suggested by th=
ese SEC and Finra inquiries.=C2=A0On the other hand, you do like to see Rob=
inhood eating its own cooking. It is the leading brokerage for YOLOing meme=
 stocks. Lots of people, particularly in the financial industry, think that=
 YOLOing meme stocks is bad for you. If everyone at Robinhood thought that =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0if none of them were YOLOing meme stocks in their personal a=
ccounts =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that would be awkward; it would suggest that th=
ey are knowingly taking advantage of, and encouraging, poor decisions by th=
eir customers.=C2=A0If instead everyone at Robinhood piled into GameStop to=
o, that=E2=80=99s sort of nice; it suggests that they believe in what they=
=E2=80=99re selling.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s another=
 update from the prospectus:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fu=
rther, on July 26, 2021, [Robinhood]=C2=A0received a FINRA investigative re=
quest seeking documents and information related to its compliance with FINR=
A registration requirements for member personnel, including related to the =
FINRA non-registration status of Mr. Tenev and Mr. Bhatt. Robinhood is eval=
uating this matter and intends to cooperate with the investigation.</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See, the Financial Industry Regulator=
y Authority=C2=A0licenses brokers, and if you work in certain jobs at a bro=
ker-dealer you need a Finra license, and I guess Robinhood Chief Executive =
Officer Vlad Tenev <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/24580483.273146/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25uLmNvbS8yMDIxLzA3LzI3L2ludmVzdGluZy9yb2=
Jpbmhvb2QtaXBvLWZpbnJhLXZsYWQtdGVuZXYvaW5kZXguaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBd7ee0fc5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">doesn=E2=80=99t have one</a>? Honestly this seems like a bit of a silly =
thing to care about but the rules are the rules. I hope that Vlad Tenev has=
 to show up at a Prometric testing center to take his <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24580483.273146/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmlucmE=
ub3JnL3JlZ2lzdHJhdGlvbi1leGFtcy1jZS9xdWFsaWZpY2F0aW9uLWV4YW1zL3Nlcmllczc/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb20b5274" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">Series 7</a> with a bunch of 22-year-old Wall Street=
 analysts. You don=E2=80=99t often see celebrities at the Series 7.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/24580483.273146/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjcvcm9iaW5ob29kLXdvcmtpbmctb24tZmVhdHVyZS10by1s=
ZXQtdXNlcnMtaW52ZXN0LXNwYXJlLWNoYW5nZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0dd01caf" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> another up=
date</a> that is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>from the revised prospectus:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood Markets Inc. is exploring n=
ew features that would let customers invest spare change and better protect=
 against volatility in cryptocurrency trading, according to code hidden ins=
ide a test version of the company=E2=80=99s iPhone app.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Robinhood is developing an option called =E2=80=9Cround up inv=
estments=E2=80=9D that will allow users to invest their spare change in spe=
cific stocks, according to the code, which was part of a version of the app=
 distributed to beta testers earlier this month. The code also shows that t=
he company is exploring a rewards program that will give bonuses to those u=
sing the round-up feature.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investing spare =
change has become an increasingly popular strategy for new stock traders an=
d is a key piece of competing apps such as Acorns, Chime and Wealthsimple. =
The code in the Robinhood app doesn=E2=80=99t indicate where the spare chan=
ge will come from, but other apps typically connect to a debit or credit ca=
rd. They round up purchases to the nearest dollar and automatically invest =
that difference. For example, if a user spends $3.75 on a cup of coffee, 25=
 cents will be put toward a chosen stock.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Or if you spend $8.75 on a large popcorn at an AMC Entertainmen=
